    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Can you go into more detail on what happens if *only* the pitot tube is blocked but the static port stays clear? I've heard that it can sometimes make the airspeed indicator act like an altimeter. Why does that happen?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When only the pitot tube is blocked, but the static port remains clear, the airspeed indicator starts to behave like an altimeter because the instrument is essentially being fed incorrect pressure data. The airspeed indicator relies on the *difference* between the total pressure (from the pitot) and the static pressure (from the static port) to calculate airspeed. If the pitot pressure reading is stuck at the ambient static pressure—because the blockage prevents the dynamic pressure from reaching it—the difference becomes zero, or near zero. This effectively makes the instrument read the static pressure as if it were the total pressure, which is what an altimeter does when it reads altitude based on ambient pressure.",
      "source": "target",
